abstract: JACKSON, Ky., Nov. 1. -- Jackson and Breathitt Counties are quiet on the surface to-night, after an exciting day. Militia arrived here from Lexington today, and departed later for Crockettsville, the stronghold of former Sheriff Edward Callahan. The streets were thronged with armed mountain men all day, while groups of citizens discussed the tense political situation and others gathered at the station to await the arrival of more troops from Cynthiana.

abstract: BALTIMORE, Md., Nov. 2. -- Election day and beautiful weather brought out the biggest crowd of the meeting at Pimlico to-day. The Walden Stake, the Fall feature at this track, was won by Fauntleroy, the odds-on favorite, without being unduly extended. The race came very near being ruined at the start, one of the assistant starters hanging on a bit too long to Rosshampton, causing him to stumble and throw his jockey.

abstract: MAY'S LANDING, N.J., Nov. 2. -- The season for killing deer in New Jersey opens to-morrow, after being closed for ten years. Almost every train to-day brought hunting parties, and many sportsmen arrived in automobiles and went direct to the deer woods. In some instances they pitched tents and will camp out so they can be on the drives and stands early.

abstract: BOSTON, Nov. 2. -- Massachusetts registered disapproval of the Aldrich tariff by cutting down Gov. Draper's plurality greatly. abstract: ANNAPOLIS, Md., Nov. 5. -- For the first time in several years midshipmen at the Naval Academy to-day revived "the silence," which is as old as the academy itself. abstract: BURLINGTON, N.J., Nov. 6. -- The masked robber who blew open with dynamite a safe at the farm house of Schuyler Rainier of Florence, the township's richest farmer, yesterday afternoon and got away with over $3,000 in cash, overlooked bonds and valuables of more than $100,000. Pennsylvania Railroad bonds of a value of $8,000, supposed to have been taken by the robber, were found to-day in a pile of rubbish.

abstract: Antonio Monasterio, a Cuban planter, arrived Wednesday evening on the steamship George Washington. abstract: OF all the beautiful towers for which New York is famous none has the peculiar interest of the one on the Seventy-first Regiment Armory, at Thirty-fourth Street and Park Avenue. abstract: MR. SYMONS, writing very ingeniously of Coleridge, in this remarkable, almost uncanny book* of criticism, is very severe on Coleridge's weakness for disciples. abstract: CHICAGO, Ill., Nov. 22. -- During a heavy storm which raged on Lake Michigan to-day, the steamer Puritan of the Graham  Morton Line became disabled off New Buffalo, where she lies to-night without her rudder. abstract: SYRACUSE, N.Y., Nov. 23. -- A conference of representatives of ten or more temperance societies of the State was held here to-day to decide on a State-wide prohibition movement. abstract: NEW YORK'S new prison at Bear Mountain on the Hudson resembles just now some crude and exceedingly picturesque frontier stockade. abstract: BERLIN, Nov. 28. -- The Reichstag will reconvene Tuesday, the Emperor returning to Berlin to open the session personally.
